{{Other people|Charles Robinson}} {{Infobox Politician | name = Charles Robinson | image = | imagesize = 180px | office1 = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|Ontario MPP]] | term_start1 = 1879 | term_end1 = 1883 | predecessor1 = [[John Flesher]] | successor1 = [[William Henry Hammell]] | constituency1 = [[Cardwell (provincial electoral district)|Cardwell]] | party = [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal]] | birth_date = {{birth date|1835|11|4}} | birth_place = [[Chinguacousy Township, Ontario|Chinguacousy Township]], [[York County, Ontario|York County]], [[Upper Canada]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1898|10|17|1835|11|4}} | death_place = [[Peel County, Ontario]] | occupation = Physician | relations = | spouse = {{marriage |Helen Standing|1869}} | children = }} '''Charles Robinson''' (November 4, 1835 - October 17, 1898) was an [[Ontario]] physician and political figure. He represented [[Cardwell (provincial electoral district)|Cardwell]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] from 1879 to 1883 as a [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal]] member.
He was born in [[Chinguacousy Township, Ontario|Chinguacousy Township]], [[York County, Ontario|York County]], [[Upper Canada]] in 1835. His father was of [[England|English]] descent and his mother was [[Scotland|Scottish]]. Robinson studied at the [[University of Toronto|Toronto School of Medicine]] and the [[Thomas Jefferson University|Jefferson Medical College]]. He set up practice in [[Claude, Ontario|Claude]] in [[Peel County, Ontario|Peel County]]. In 1869, he married Helen Standing. Robinson served eight years as coroner.
