'''Jury stress''' or '''juror stress''' is physical and mental [[wikt:tension|tension]] that affects members of [[Jury|juries]].  Its causes include "[[Fatigue (physical)|exhaustion]], [[Jury sequestration|sequestration]], the mountain of evidence, and the desire to do the right thing".<ref>{{cite book |title=Nolo's Plain-English Law Dictionary |last=Hill |first=Gerald |author2=Kathleen Hill |author3=Nolo (Firm) |year=2009 |publisher=Nolo |location= |isbn= 9781413310375 |page=239 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FG9X-8LNT1IC&lpg=PA239&dq=%22JURY%20STRESS%22&pg=PA239#v=onepage&q=%22JURY%20STRESS%22&f=false |accessdate=September 3, 2010}}</ref>

